            "author_info": {
                "name": "Graham C Lindsay",
                "href": "/profile/Graham-C-Lindsay"
            },
            "answer_text": "The draft should never be considered a finishing point but only a start to work from. It would be rather radical to completely destroy the draft and start again from scratch but in the process of going through several drafting stages by the time you get to the completed work you could easily see a vast difference between the started draft and the completed final edit. For example depending on the flow of the novel you might find a beautifully written chapter that just simply does not fit into this particular novel, instead of discarding completely place it in your \u201cto be used for future novels\u201d drawer. To me writing is like music, the trumpet solo sounds wonderful but if the story is about strings then that trumpet solo needs to go. Thank you for the question. ",
