                "name": "Kris Munro",
                "href": "/profile/Kris-Munro"
            },
            "answer_text": "You\u2019ll find there\u2019s not much difference between the two choices. It\u2019s rare that, for beginner writers, the first draft will consist of sections that remain untouched. Where you decide to place your alterations (new or old document) isn\u2019t really as important as how well you make your improvements. It really comes down to whether you want to preserve your first draft. And this becomes a moot point because you should be making backups as you progress. If you\u2019re asking this question, I would assume that you\u2019ve spent a good amount of time writing what could be your first novel. This leads me to believe that you\u2019ve already put a lot of time and attention to your first \u2018draft\u2019.. which means it may not be entirely \u2018draft-like\u2019. I\u2019d recommend editing what you\u2019ve already got. ",
